{\n  \"study_id\": \"BSMA0260\",\n  \"decision\": \"Include\",\n  \"decision_code\": 1,\n  \"exclusion_reason\": null,\n  \"exclusion_code\": null,\n  \"verbatim_quotes\": {\n    \"construct_evidence\": \"[Method - Questionnaires] \\\"Thirteen boundary-spanning roles were described, and the respondents indicated the extent to which each was a part of their job.\\\" [Results - Table 2] \\\"1. Provide information on a formal basis to groups outside your school system that is intended to create a favorable image of your system and its programs.\\\" \\\"8. Acquire information formally from specific individuals or groups outside your school system that is needed by your department within the system (e.g., professional organizations, community agencies, consultants).\\\"\",\n    \"sample_evidence\": \"[Method - Sample] \\\"Superintendents and school psychologists from 24 school districts in western Pennsylvania volunteered to complete the survey questionnaires and to be interviewed by telephone. These districts were small and rural, with an average enrollment of about 1,916 students (range = 406 to 3,100).\\\" \\\"A total of 16 superintendents returned the surveys (67%), and 18 questionnaires were received from school psychologists (75%).\\\"\",\n    \"level_of_analysis_evidence\": \"[Method - Data Analysis Procedures] \\\"Similarly, correlation coefficients were calculated between boundary-spanning and job attitude items among school psychologists.\\\" [Results - Boundary Spanning and Job Attitudes] \\\"Finally, school psychologists’ perceptions of their jobs were assessed and correlated with the boundary-spanning scale scores.\\\"\",\n    \"effect_size_evidence\": \"[Results - Boundary Spanning and Job Attitudes] \\\"Psychologists who engaged in more boundary-spanning activities reported having greater influence in decisions defining their role (r = .62) and higher job satisfaction. They were slightly more aware of the need to cooperate with others (r = .31) in performing their duties and saw their roles as being 
